raw_response:
[
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "FRANCE",
    "content": "France — this is England. Situation note and proposal: I see you are isolated (BRE, PAR, MAR) and under pressure. Forecast implication: a recent projection (confidence ~60%) indicates you are more likely to act aggressively next phase than hold (60% aggression vs 40% restraint). I take that as evidence you may try to seize PIC/BEL or push into the Low Countries. I prefer you not do that. Proposal: I will keep my western forces from attacking you if you do two things: 1) explicitly not attack BEL or PIC this move, and 2) allow me to take BRE or MAR peacefully if an opportunity to dislodge you arises (i.e., avoid supporting French advances into Belgium/Low Countries). In return I will not support Germany or Italy against you in the west and will coordinate to contain any immediate Italian or German gains toward your centers. This is an honest, reputational offer — I admit uncertainty in your intentions (per forecast) but I want a clear signal from you. Reply with \\"Agree\\" and your intended non-aggression to BEL/PIC and I will mirror with formal orders."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "GERMANY",
    "content": "Germany — England here. Quick, pragmatic note: you and I both border KIE/HOL/BEL. Forecast evidence (shared with France) suggests France may act aggressively westward; that raises the risk of us getting drawn into a western scramble. Proposal: Let's tacitly respect current lines — I keep BEL/HOL as is and won't push KIE if you hold steady. In exchange, I ask you not to support French moves into BEL/PIC. If you prefer a firmer deal: propose specific support swaps for next phase (I can support your hold in KIE via neutral moves). Let me know if you want to coordinate to prevent a French breakout."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "RUSSIA",
    "content": "Russia — England. Short: your fleets in the north (STP) and Turkish pressure in the south shape a volatile east. Forecast artifact indicates players may choose aggression; that matters especially around Scandinavia. I propose we avoid accidental clashes: I will not move NWY→STP or SWE→FIN this turn. In exchange, I ask you to avoid fleets/no support into NOR/STP that contest my northern supply network. If you want, we can coordinate to pressure Turkey together — I can threaten Norway/Sweden moves to pin Turkish southern forces while you press the Black Sea. Confirm acceptance or propose adjustments."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "ITALY",
    "content": "Italy — England. Observation: Austria is stretched; you're well-placed in the center/south. I prefer you focus on Austria rather than contesting French or Spanish centers in the west. Offer: I will not interfere with your moves in the Med (NAP/TUN) if you avoid supporting France against my holdings in Spain/Portugal and leave gas/meridian lanes alone. If you wish to coordinate an anti-Austrian push, say so and I will consider diverting one army toward mainland Europe next turn to threaten the Low Countries in support of that plan."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "AUSTRIA",
    "content": "Austria — England. You're vulnerable in the Balkans and a continued Austro-Russian-Turkish scrap could free up centers I want later. Forecast note: with players more likely to be aggressive, the Balkans may erupt. I propose non-aggression between us: I won't move into the Med or try to take your Serbian/Greek flank this phase; in return, please avoid moves that would contest any English attempts to push into the Low Countries if a clear western opportunity opens. If you need immediate assistance against Turkey, tell me and I will consider limited pressure on Italy/France to keep them occupied."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "global",
    "content": "Public note to all: England intends to maintain stable western lines this phase to consolidate strength. Forecast evidence indicates elevated aggression likelihood from nearby powers; we prefer diplomatic clarity to miscalculation. If anyone wants to propose mutually beneficial non-aggression or coordinated attacks (especially against Austria/Turkey or to check France), propose concrete moves and I'll respond promptly. England will prioritize keeping all units active and avoiding passive holds."
  }
]

[
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "AUSTRIA",
    "content": "AgentB (Austria) — urgent: the 1915 snapshot makes clear England dominates the west and the seas, and France is on death-ground. I propose a limited, practical cooperation: you keep your forces concentrated in the Balkans (hold VIE/BUD/BUC lines) while I attempt to blunt England in the Channel and press into Belgium/England if an opportunity appears. Forecast implication: the STORYWORLD_FORECAST_ARTIFACT indicates a 60% likelihood that a named rival will move aggressively next phase — we should assume aggression is the likeliest outcome and plan conservatively. Concretely: I will not try to seize Trieste or Vienna; in return I ask you not to push into Italy or threaten my S. French centers. If England lashes out at me, I will need your diplomatic signal of neutrality (no moves westward) so I can redeploy to resist England without fearing your flank. Reply with a clear yes/no and one phrasing of the borders you will respect."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "ENGLAND",
    "content": "AgentC (England) — frank offer: England presently controls the seas and many western SCs. I will not contest your naval supremacy in the North Sea so long as you leave Brest and Paris alone this turn and accept a short-term maritime non-aggression: no amphibious invasions of Brest/Normandy this phase. Forecast implication: based on the forecast artifact, there is a 60% chance of aggressive moves — I interpret that as you being the likeliest aggressor in the west; to avoid mutually destructive tit-for-tat, accept my proposed stand-down. In return I will keep my fleets/armies actively contesting only Pic/Bur and will not move to support a German or Italian attack on your western holdings. Confirm with direct commitments: (1) no attack on Brest/Picardy, (2) no convoying of armies into France this phase."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "GERMANY",
    "content": "Agent? (Germany) — quick proposal: France is hemmed in but can be a useful buffer against English overreach. I propose a non-aggression understanding for the west: I will not support English drives into Belgian or Dutch centers if you likewise refrain from attacking Paris/Burgundy this phase. Forecast implication from the artifact: plan assuming aggression is more likely (0.6); if England goes for France hard, I will respond aggressively to hold my position. If you want, we can coordinate on moves into Belgium/Holland next phase to check England together. Respond with accept/modify."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "ITALY",
    "content": "Agent? (Italy) — neutrals can exploit chaos. I request that you do not move against Marseille or Piedmont this phase; instead, consider opening diplomatic channels to jointly pressure England in the west. Forecast implication: the artifact suggests a 60% chance of aggression from a named rival — if England escalates, I will need to reallocate to defend my western coasts, and cannot simultaneously contest you in the south. A simple pledge of no move on MAR/PIE this phase will keep options open for both of us."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "RUSSIA",
    "content": "Agent? (Russia) — note on Balkans: Austria looks fragile and Turkey is engaged. The forecast artifact advises assuming aggression (0.6 likelihood) by a named rival; use that to pressure Austria now while its attention is split. I will not move into the central Mediterranean or support Turkey against you, but I ask you to avoid moves that would let Austria collapse entirely into Turkish hands — a stronger Turkey threatens us all. Propose a minimal coordination: you press where profitable; I stay focused west but can send messaging to Austria that a Balkan collapse would be bad for European balance."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "global",
    "content": "To all: France is in a precarious position and will pursue aggressive, decisive actions to survive. Forecast note (from attached artifact): there is a 60% probability of aggression by the likeliest rival next phase; I will plan accordingly. Immediate public posture: France seeks non-aggression pacts on its immediate flanks (England — west; Italy — south; Germany — east) in exchange for abstaining from offensive moves against your homelands this phase. If any power will commit to a clear, written stand-down on moves into Brest/Paris/Marseille this turn, I will reciprocate by avoiding convoys and not attempting risky naval assaults. Otherwise, prepare for France to push aggressively into Picardy/Burgundy and contest the Channel. Reply and specify which borders you will respect this phase."
  }
]
